The side length of the square is {eq}l = 1.3\;{\rm{ m}}

{/eq}


The point midway between two given positive charge is also the center line of square. Hence, the potential from all the charges at this point in the square is converted into potential due to two negative charges only.


The potential due to a point charge is expressed as,

{eq}V = \dfrac{{kq}}{r}

{/eq}

Where,

The value of the electric field constant is {eq}k = 8.99 \times {10^9}\;{{\rm{N}} \cdot {{\rm{m}}^2}} / {{\rm{C}}^2}

{/eq}.
The distance from the center of the square to the negative charge is denoted as {eq}r

{/eq}.


When the point midway between two given positive charge is converted into a point midway between two negative charges are taken, then the distance from the center of the square to the negative charge is expressed as,

{eq}r = \dfrac{{\sqrt 2 }}{2}l

{/eq}

Where,

{eq}\sqrt 2

{/eq} represents square root of two.


Substituting all these values in the equation of the potential owing to a point charge.



{eq}\begin{align*}

V &= \dfrac{{k\left( {2q} \right)}}{r}\\

V &= \dfrac{{k\left( {2q} \right)}}{{\dfrac{{\sqrt 2 }}{2}l}}\\

V &= \dfrac{{2kq}}{{\dfrac{{\sqrt 2 }}{2}l}}\\

V &= \dfrac{{2kq \times 2}}{{\sqrt 2 l}}......\left( 1 \right)

\end{align*}

{/eq}



Substituting all known values in equation (1).


{eq}\begin{align*}

V &= \dfrac{{2 \times 8.99 \times {{10}^9} \times 5.2 \times {{10}^{ - 9}} \times 2}}{{\sqrt 2 \times 1.3}}\\

V &= \dfrac{{2 \times 8.99 \times 5.2}}{\sqrt 2 }\\

V &= 44.0058\;{\rm{V}}

\end{align*}

{/eq}



